In this attempt indeed, it having been the chief object of the Translator to keep as close as possible to his author, hc would have found little room for the display of poetic talent, had he possessed it; and he has only to hope that he may be found to have kept clear of mean and hemely, or inappropriate diction, though he cannot expect to have found a language in any degree worthy of the original.

In the course of the undertaking he has avoided borrowing from the published labours of others, though he has occasionally consulted former translations, and compared them with his own. To name Dryden, and to have ventured upon the same ground with him, may appear bold and presuming3 but it may be admitted that the coarseness of some of his lines is not suitable , to the taste of the present age3 and besides, Dryden's Satires are not regular translations, but in many parts deviate into parody and imitation.
